iverges from ER. Notably, it also argues that the 1994 deal=E2=80=99s freez=
e provision only applies to =E2=80=9Cderivative works,=E2=80=9D which
they claim The Pitt is not.

This tactic, however, is hardly foolproof. First, the distinctiveness of Th=
e Pitt remains questionable, with Warners cloaking key details under the pr=
etense of avoiding =E2=80=9Cspoilers=E2=80=9D that might dampen viewer inte=
rest=E2=80=94a claim that strains credulity, as it=E2=80=99s rare for the e=
xposure of character names or basic plot outlines to deter audience engagem=
ent. This overcaution might suggest a lack of confidence in its legal posit=
ion, too. A true cynic might even accuse Warner Bros. of going back and for=
ensically, painstakingly, removing anything in The Pitt=E2=80=99s treatment=
 and pilot script that had even a whiff of ER.

Moreover, it is improbable that the court will regard the Crichton estate a=
s a typical plaintiff, similar to a disgruntled writer who emerges from now=
here to claim a studio plagiarized their script. Judge Chang might instead =
view the situation like the ongoing controversy ( https://puck.news/live-pd=
-the-legal-perils-of-uncancel-culture/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B=
+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F12%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ) over Live PD, =
where the show=E2=80=99s producer has been accused of repackaging a similar=
 program to circumvent A&E=E2=80=99s exclusive rights. (Incidentally, Gibso=
n Dunn is representing the defendant in that case, too.)

It=E2=80=99s not a foregone conclusion that copyright principles will be de=
cisive, either. When Crichton=E2=80=99s attorney, Robert Klieger, responds,=
 he=E2=80=99s likely to emphasize that this is fundamentally a contract cas=
e, and that a =E2=80=9Cderivative work=E2=80=9D could merely mean anything =
derived from ER, including a project involving the same showrunner, writers=
, star actor, and studio after a full year of negotiations. If The Pitt can=
 be traced back to ER in
any manner, Klieger will urge discovery as the prudent path.

Of course, the Crichton side must contend with the reality that ER is hardl=
y the only drama set in a hospital. There have been too many to count over =
the years, including several also set in Chicago, such as Chicago Med and C=
hicago Hope. Judge Chang might want to leave room for Warners to pivot to s=
ome other area of the genre that=E2=80=99s outside of the ER universe and t=
he ambit of the freeze provision. Where, exactly, that line is drawn is dif=
ficult to pinpoint, making this case all the more fascinating and one to wa=
tch closely.

Because few have actually seen the The Pitt, it=E2=80=99s hard to prognosti=
cate how this legal drama will play out. For one, it=E2=80=99s more than po=
ssible that the judge refuses to let Warners keep the series=E2=80=99 legal=
ly crucial plot details under seal. In any case, the rest of us will get a =
clearer view soon. Although Crichton=E2=80=99s
complaint originally asked for injunctive relief, her legal team has since =
elected not to pursue any attempt to halt the release of the series. So The=
 Pitt will likely premiere in the spring, even as the legal battle proceeds=
, perhaps moving into the discovery phase if Warners=E2=80=99 bid to dismis=
s is unsuccessful. Either way, it=E2=80=99s very doubtful this will be reso=
lved by the end of Noah Wyle=E2=80=99s shift.

Thanks, Eriq. I=E2=80=99ll be back on Thursday.

Matt

