agement in <b>David Zaslav</b> and Warner Bros. Discovery. But the most sig=
nificant issue arose from the great beyond: the fiercely protective estate =
of <b>Michael Crichton</b>, the bestselling author who turned his experienc=
e as an emergency room intern in the 1970s into the NBC series that dominat=
ed TV from 1994 to 2009. <b>Sherri</b> <b>Crichton</b>, the author=E2=80=99=
s widow, was already peeved that her late husband had been short-changed wh=
en HBO rebooted <i>Westworld</i>=E2=80=94and began making a fuss over how h=
e=E2=80=99d be credited on the <i>ER</i>
reboot, too. <br/><br/>Negotiations fell apart last year. But this past Mar=
ch, nearly six months after the reboot hopes had faded, WBTV and its sister=
