ecognition of the late writer=E2=80=99s contribution to the reboot. =E2=80=
=9CBut no deal was reached, and Defendants had no choice but to move on,=E2=
=80=9D the studio=E2=80=99s anti-SLAPP motion states. =E2=80=9CWhen they de=
cided to make <i>The Pitt</i>, they made sure to create a drama that was ve=
ry different from <i>ER</i>.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Essentially, WBTV=E2=80=99s
argument is that <i>The Pitt</i> isn=E2=80=99t a recycled <i>ER</i>, and th=
e studio owes Sherri nothing since she doesn=E2=80=99t have a monopoly on m=
edical dramas. To win, a judge must be convinced to look past a year=E2=80=
=99s worth of negotiations and focus solely on how the forthcoming show div=
erges from its predecessor. For example, it appears that unlike <i>ER</i>, =
<i>The Pitt</i> is a =E2=80=9Creal-time=E2=80=9D drama, similar to <i>24</i=
>, with each episode tracking one hour of a 15-hour shift that comprises th=
