x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Warner Bros. TV=E2=
=80=99s legal strategy is likely to rely on the differences between <i>The =
Pitt </i>and the scrubbed <i>ER</i> reboot, and the sheer number of medical=
 dramas in the public consciousness. It=E2=80=99s clear from a review of th=
e anti-SLAPP motion that the studio=E2=80=99s lawyers at Gibson Dunn will a=
ttempt to steer a breach of contract lawsuit toward a copyright analysis. T=
his strategy is understandable in a legal landscape where plaintiffs seldom=
 triumph after judges sift through unprotectable genre tropes to focus sole=
ly on the similarity of expression. <br/><br/>While the motion is heavily r=
edacted, Warners elaborates on the characters, plot, themes, and dialogue o=
f <i>The Pitt</i> to demonstrate how the new series diverges from <i>ER</i>=
=2E Notably, it also argues that the=
 1994 deal=E2=80=99s freeze provision onl=
y applies to =E2=80=9Cderivative works,=E2=80=9D which
they claim <i>The Pitt</i> is not. <br/><br/>This tactic, however, is hardl=
y foolproof. First, the distinctiveness of <i>The Pitt</i> remains question=
able, with Warners cloaking key details under the pretense of avoiding =E2=
=80=9Cspoilers=E2=80=9D that might dampen viewer interest=E2=80=94a claim t=
hat strains credulity, as it=E2=80=99s rare for the exposure of character n=
ames or basic plot outlines to deter audience engagement. This overcaution =
might suggest a lack of confidence in its legal position, too. A true cynic=
 might even accuse Warner Bros. of going back and forensically, painstaking=
ly, removing <i>anything</i> in <i>The Pitt</i>=E2=80=99s treatment and pil=
ot script that had even a whiff of <i>ER</i>.<br/><br/>Moreover, it is impr=
obable that the court will regard the Crichton estate as a typical plaintif=
f, similar to a disgruntled writer who emerges from nowhere to claim a stud=
io plagiarized their script. Judge Chang might instead view the situation l=
ike the <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z=
1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUSXhhbHl2ckRUY1NQU2d5VklDND0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNr=
Lm5ld3MvbGl2ZS1wZC10aGUtbGVnYWwtcGVyaWxzLW9mLXVuY2FuY2VsLWN1bHR1cmUvP3V0bV9=
jYW1wYWlnbj1XaGF0K0klMjdtK0hlYXJpbmclMkIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgxMSUyRjEyJT=
JGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN=
2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoxMTM3MTcyfQ/a3a5dbe7c0a92f7639462c6b87eae0153=
57792a77d7bc11a10ffb2d726f06f7b" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:non=
e;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">ongoing controversy</a></u> over <i>Live =
PD</i>, where the show=E2=80=99s producer has been accused of repackaging a=
 similar program to circumvent A&amp;E=E2=80=99s exclusive rights. (Inciden=
tally, Gibson Dunn is representing the defendant in that case, too.)<br/><b=
r/>It=E2=80=99s not a foregone conclusion that copyright principles will be=
 decisive, either. When Crichton=E2=80=99s attorney, <b>Robert Klieger</b>,=
 responds, he=E2=80=99s likely to emphasize that this is fundamentally a <i=
>contract</i> case, and that a =E2=80=9Cderivative work=E2=80=9D could mere=
ly mean anything <i>derived</i> from <i>ER</i>, including a project involvi=
ng the same showrunner, writers, star actor, and studio after a full year o=
f negotiations. If <i>The Pitt</i> can be traced back to <i>ER</i> in
any manner, Klieger will urge discovery as the prudent path.<br/><br/>Of co=
urse, the Crichton side must contend with the reality that <i>ER</i> is har=
dly the only drama set in a hospital. There have been too many to count ove=
r the years, including several <i>also</i> set in Chicago, such as <i>Chica=
go Med</i> and <i>Chicago Hope</i>. Judge Chang might want to leave room fo=
r Warners to pivot to some other area of the genre that=E2=80=99s outside o=
f the <i>ER</i> universe and the ambit of the freeze provision. Where, exac=
tly, that line is drawn is difficult to pinpoint, making this case all the =
more fascinating and one to watch closely.<br/><br/>Because few have actual=
ly <i>seen</i> the <i>The Pitt</i>, it=E2=80=99s hard to prognosticate how =
this legal drama will play out. For one, it=E2=80=99s more than possible th=
at the judge refuses to let Warners keep the series=E2=80=99 legally crucia=
l plot details under seal. In any case, the rest of us will get a clearer v=
iew soon. Although Crichton=E2=80=99s
complaint originally asked for injunctive relief, her legal team has since =
elected not to pursue any attempt to halt the release of the series. So <i>=
The Pitt</i> will likely premiere in the spring, even as the legal battle p=
roceeds, perhaps moving into the discovery phase if Warners=E2=80=99 bid to=
 dismiss is unsuccessful. Either way, it=E2=80=99s very doubtful this will =
be resolved by the end of Noah Wyle=E2=80=99s shift.<br/></td>
